### History

The narrative of Keiser University begins in **1977**, a year marked by the founding of **The Keiser School** in [Fort Lauderdale, Florida](/Fort_Lauderdale,_Florida). This ambitious undertaking was the brainchild of **Arthur Keiser** and his mother, **Evelyn**. Their vision was clear: to establish an institution that would prepare students for the burgeoning job market in Florida, particularly in the fields of business and healthcare, which were experiencing significant growth.

By **1982**, the educational offerings had expanded. The inclusion of programs in paralegal studies and computer technology prompted a rebranding to **Keiser Institute of Technology**. This new name reflected the institution's broadened technological and professional focus. The pace of development continued, and in **1986**, the school achieved a significant milestone by beginning to award associate degrees. This expansion in academic credentials led to another name change, this time to **Keiser College**. The dawn of the new millennium brought further academic ambition, with Keiser establishing its first bachelor's degree programs in **2001**. The institution's trajectory was clearly upward, and in **2006**, it underwent its final and most significant name transformation, officially becoming **Keiser University**.

The year **2010** saw Keiser University, along with several other for-profit educational institutions in Florida, come under scrutiny from the [Florida Attorney General](/Florida_Attorney_General). However, by **2012**, this investigation was concluded with Keiser entering into an "assurance of voluntary compliance," suggesting a resolution that did not involve formal charges. A pivotal shift occurred in **2011** when the university transitioned from a for-profit to a not-for-profit operational model. This change was facilitated by Arthur Keiser's sale of the institution for an undisclosed sum to Everglades College Inc., a [non-profit](/Non-profit) entity also founded by Keiser, which also oversees [Everglades University](/Everglades_University). This move signaled a new phase in the university's financial and operational structure.

In **2015**, Keiser University significantly expanded its physical presence by acquiring a 100-acre site in West Palm Beach. This land, formerly the Florida campus of [Northwood University](/Northwood_University), was transformed into the university's flagship residential campus. The objective was to provide students with a more immersive, traditional residential educational experience. The following year, **2016**, marked a notable academic expansion with the launch of the university's College of [Chiropractic](/Chiropractic) Medicine. Under the deanship of Dr. Michael Wiles, this initiative represented the establishment of the first chiropractic program of its kind in [South Florida](/South_Florida).

**2017** saw Keiser University's Chancellor, Arthur Keiser, take on a prominent role in national educational policy. He assumed the chairmanship of the U.S. Department of Education's [National Advisory Committee on Institutional Quality and Integrity](/National_Advisory_Committee_on_Institutional_Quality_and_Integrity) (NACIQI). Keiser's involvement with this committee was not new; he had initially been appointed by then Secretary of Education [Margaret Spellings](/Margaret_Spellings) and had been reappointed twice subsequently by Republican administrations, underscoring his sustained influence in the higher education sector.

### Licensure and Accreditation

Keiser University holds a crucial accreditation from the Commission on Colleges of the [Southern Association of Colleges and Schools](/Southern_Association_of_Colleges_and_Schools), which empowers it to grant certificates and degrees across associate, baccalaureate, master's, and doctoral levels. Beyond this overarching accreditation, the university is also licensed by the Commission for Independent Education in Florida, ensuring compliance with state-specific educational regulations.

### Recognition and Rankings

Keiser University has garnered recognition in various national rankings, reflecting its performance and impact in higher education. While rankings can be a complex and sometimes contentious metric, they offer a snapshot of how institutions are perceived and evaluated.

*   In the **2022-23** reporting year, [U.S. News & World Report](/U.S._News_%26_World_Report) placed Keiser University at **#219** in its National Universities category, sharing this position with other institutions. Notably, the publication also ranked Keiser **#1** for Top Performers on Social Mobility, highlighting its success in serving students from disadvantaged backgrounds.
*   The **2021** edition of [U.S. News & World Report](/U.S._News_%26_World_Report) ranked Keiser University **#284** (tie) among all national universities. It also ranked **#11** (tie) in the category of "Top Performers of Social Mobility."
*   For **2020**, [U.S. News & World Report](/U.S._News_%26_World_Report) listed Keiser University at **#272** (tie) in its national university rankings and **#34** (tie) for "Top Performers of Social Mobility."
*   In **2019**, [Washington Monthly](/Washington_Monthly) positioned Keiser University at **263rd** out of 395 institutions on its national universities list. This ranking methodology emphasizes social mobility, research contributions, and the promotion of public service.
*   The **2018** rankings by [Money](/Money_(magazine)) magazine identified Keiser University - Fort Lauderdale as the **#8** top college for value in Florida.

### Athletics

The athletic endeavors of Keiser University are represented by the **[Seahawks](/Keiser_Seahawks)**. The university is an active member of the [National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics](/National_Association_of_Intercollegiate_Athletics) (NAIA). Since the **2015–16 academic year**, the Seahawks have primarily competed in **[The Sun](/Sun_Conference)**, a conference formerly known as the Florida Sun Conference (FSC) until the conclusion of the 2007–08 school year. Prior to July 2015, the athletic teams represented [Northwood University](/Northwood_University)'s West Palm Beach campus, bearing the name [Northwood Seahawks](/Northwood_Seahawks).

Keiser University fields teams in an impressive **24 intercollegiate varsity sports**. The roster of men's sports includes baseball, basketball, cross country, football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, swimming, tennis, and track & field (both indoor and outdoor), as well as wrestling. For women, the university offers basketball, cross country, flag football, golf, lacrosse, soccer, softball, swimming, tennis, and track & field (indoor and outdoor), along with volleyball. Additionally, Keiser competes in co-ed sports such as Esports, cheerleading, and dance. The university also supports club sports, including equestrian, fishing, and golf, further broadening the opportunities for student-athletes.

